    <h2 id="key-features">8. Key Features & Technology</h2>
    <p>Understanding the technical aspects of Western Refrigeration products helps you assess whether they meet your business requirements. Here is a detailed look at the key features across the product range.</p>

    <h3>Energy Efficiency</h3>
    <p>Western has made significant strides in energy efficiency over the past decade. Most of their 2025-2026 lineup carries BEE star ratings where applicable. Their visi coolers and deep freezers in the 200L to 500L range typically consume 2 to 6 units of electricity per day, depending on ambient temperature and how frequently the unit is opened.</p>
    <p>Compared to unbranded or locally assembled commercial refrigeration units (which are common in Indian markets and consume 30-50% more power), Western products are noticeably more energy efficient. However, compared to premium brands like Blue Star or Godrej, the energy savings are marginal — Western competes primarily on purchase price rather than running cost.</p>

    <h3>Build Quality</h3>
    <p>Western uses pre-coated galvanized steel for the outer body and aluminium or coated wire shelving inside. The finish quality is functional rather than premium — you will not get the polished stainless steel look of a Blue Star or Voltas commercial unit. The powder coating on the exterior is durable and rust-resistant, suitable for Indian commercial environments, though it may show wear after 3-4 years of heavy use in humid locations like coastal cities.</p>
    <p>The insulation is high-density polyurethane foam (PUF), which is the industry standard. Insulation thickness varies from 40mm on smaller units to 65mm on larger deep freezers and visi coolers. This is adequate for most Indian conditions, though in extreme-heat zones (Rajasthan, Vidarbha, parts of Gujarat itself), you may notice the compressor working harder during peak summer.</p>

    <h3>Compressor Types</h3>
    <p>Western uses a mix of compressor brands across their product lines:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Tecumseh:</strong> The most common choice across their visi cooler and deep freezer range. Tecumseh compressors are tropicalized, widely serviced in India, and offer a good balance of performance and longevity. Most Western products in the ₹20,000-60,000 range use Tecumseh.</li>
      <li><strong>Embraco (Nidec):</strong> Used in some higher-end models and display counters. Embraco compressors are known for quieter operation and slightly better energy efficiency. You will find these in premium visi coolers and display counters.</li>
      <li><strong>Indian-sourced compressors:</strong> Some entry-level 100L models may use Indian-made or Chinese compressors to keep costs down. These are adequate for light commercial use but may not last as long under heavy-duty operation.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Temperature Range & Control</h3>
    <p>Temperature control across Western's range is thermostat-based (analog dial) on most models. Higher-end display counters and some newer visi coolers offer digital temperature controllers with LED displays. The analog thermostats are reliable but less precise — temperature can vary by 1-2°C from the set point, which is acceptable for beverages and general food storage but may be a concern for sensitive items like chocolate garnishes or cream-based pastries.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Visi coolers:</strong> +2°C to +8°C range</li>
      <li><strong>Deep freezers:</strong> -18°C to -24°C (turbo models down to -28°C)</li>
      <li><strong>Chest coolers:</strong> +2°C to +10°C</li>
      <li><strong>Display counters:</strong> +2°C to +8°C</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Voltage Tolerance & Tropical Rating</h3>
    <p>One of Western's strengths is designing for Indian power conditions. Most products operate in a voltage range of 170V to 260V, with built-in voltage stabilizer circuitry on many models. This is important because inconsistent power supply is a reality in many parts of India — especially in tier-2 and tier-3 cities, and rural areas where bakeries, sweet shops, and grocery stores often operate. If you buy a premium imported commercial fridge, you might need a separate voltage stabilizer, adding ₹3,000-8,000 to your setup cost.</p>

    <!-- SECTION 9 -->
    <h2 id="after-sales">9. After-Sales Service Network</h2>
    <p>After-sales service is one of the most critical factors when buying commercial refrigeration equipment in India. A fridge that breaks down during peak summer can cost a bakery or restaurant tens of thousands in spoiled inventory. Here is how Western Refrigeration's service infrastructure stacks up.</p>

    <h3>Service Coverage</h3>
    <p>Western maintains a pan-India service network through a combination of company-owned service centres (primarily in Gujarat, Maharashtra, and NCR) and authorized third-party service partners in other states. Coverage is stronger in western and northern India, where the brand has deeper market penetration. In southern and eastern India, service response times may be longer — typically 24-72 hours in metro cities and 3-5 days in smaller towns.</p>

    <h3>Warranty Terms</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Standard warranty:</strong> 1 year comprehensive warranty on most products</li>
      <li><strong>Compressor warranty:</strong> 4 to 5 years on the compressor (varies by product line)</li>
      <li><strong>Extended warranty:</strong> Available through authorized dealers at additional cost (typically ₹2,000-5,000 for an extra year)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Dealer Network</h3>
    <p>Western distributes through hundreds of authorized dealers across India. Key markets include Gujarat, Maharashtra, Rajasthan, Madhya Pradesh, Delhi-NCR, Uttar Pradesh, Punjab, and Karnataka. The dealer network is dense in Gujarat (home state advantage) and Maharashtra, where you can find multiple dealers in most district towns. In states like Kerala, Tamil Nadu, West Bengal, and the Northeast, dealer availability is more limited.</p>

    <h3>Spare Parts Availability</h3>
    <p>Because Western uses standard Tecumseh and Embraco compressors, spare parts are widely available through general refrigeration spare parts suppliers — not just through Western's own channels. This is a significant practical advantage. If your Western deep freezer's thermostat fails, any competent local refrigeration mechanic can source a compatible replacement. This is less true for imported brands where proprietary parts can take weeks to arrive.</p>

    <h3>Service Quality — Honest Assessment</h3>
    <p>Based on user feedback and dealer interviews, Western's after-sales service is functional but not best-in-class. For comparison: Blue Star and Voltas have stronger, faster service networks. Godrej's service is similarly robust. Western's service tends to be acceptable in core markets (Gujarat, Maharashtra, North India) but can be inconsistent in peripheral markets. If you are buying Western in a region where they have limited presence, factor in the cost and availability of local third-party service.</p>

